feedback_3_2: I would do it again, it was really fascinating

response_bias_3: I think this research was about human users' level of trust in the capabilities of robotics arms, as well as how much "fault" we may attribute to a robotic arm as compared to outside factors. I think that the research may also try to draw correlations between the level of reliability that humans attribute to robotic arms (e.g., how much trust we had that the robotic arm would do its assigned task in the ball task) as compared to the level of trust/emotion we ourselves hold about robots (e.g., scale of "Strongly Disagree" to "Strongly Agree" about feeling uncomfortable working with a robotic arm).
feedback_3_2: I think it was advantageous to mirror the robotic arm's pacing with my own pacing during the "Go, 3, 2, 1," countdown transitioning to the ball and to the box. I will note that I automatically assumed the robotic arm's pacing would be proportional to how much time was remaining (e.g., that it would cross 1/3 the distance to the ball between "Go" and "3"). In addition, the only time I felt out of sync with the robotic arm was at moments of "Drop," in which I felt that I verbally heard and responded faster than the robotic arm's coding.

response_bias_3: Seeing if robotic arms are capable of doing the same as a real arm
feedback_3_2: I thought it was pretty cool seeing how a robotic arm can do similar things as a real arm

response_bias_3: How people would feel about the robotic arm before interacting with it and after, as well as how they would interact after certain knowledge was given to them.
feedback_3_2: It was cool to see how it worked and moved and I like that I know more about it now.

response_bias_3: testing how people think about robots in general and what they are capable of.
feedback_3_2: I thought it was fun and also weird. I wondered what made the robot arm move, was it code or was it making decisions for itself?

response_bias_3: I think this research might be about levels of trust people have in robotic arms.

response_bias_3: I think it was about people's ability to work with and gain trust with a robotic arm so much, so they'd be willing to bet on it.
feedback_3_2: I thought it was interesting as I'd never interacted with a robot arm before I found it a little unnerving but overall, the robot moved well, and I found I trusted what its next movements would be.

response_bias_3: It is about how/ to what degree human can trust the robotic arm after a simple team task with the robotic arm.
feedback_3_2: The robotic arm seems out of sync with the almost 80% time. I guess it is because I could hear the voice order in different paces while the robotic arm could not.

response_bias_3: I think the research was about the relationship between human trust on the robot arm and the effectiveness/results on the task performed by the robot arm. In human beings, trust on oneself or others can promote the confidence and thus increase the effectiveness. So whether we humanize the robot arm in this situation may be important.
feedback_3_2: I think it is interesting to interact with the robotic arm in this way as teamwork. You feel that the robotic arm is a good partner to study from and collaborate with. I first feared that my ball will go into the robot's box/area, but when our balls are mixed together in the box, I really felt that we are a team to achieve the same goal.

response_bias_3: I thought this research was about elements of teamwork (trust, working towards a mutual goal) as it applies to a robot. Working in coordination is an attribute of some teams depending on the type of task.
feedback_3_2: When interacting with the robotic arm, I felt I tried to move in sync with it more than it tried to move in sync with me. That may be a consequence of the fact that I assume the robot had done this more than I had and there was a bit more trust for the robot than I would ascribe to myself.

response_bias_3: I think this research is about individuals' perceptions about a robotic arm's skills/competency. I also believe it is about individuals' level of trust regarding robot arms. I believe it may also have to do with perceptions and trust changing based on an in-person activity with a robotic arm and also a computer/digital activity.
feedback_3_2: I think social science research with robotics is important as industries move more and more toward using AI and robots. Researchers/we need to know more about how people can be made more comfortable with new advanced technology like robots.

response_bias_3: I think this research was gauging human trust in the robotic arm's ability to complete a variety of tasks, ranging from easy to hard. As long as programmed appropriately, I feel the robotic arm would succeed in these tasks on a regular basis.

response_bias_3: How humans interact with and perceive robotic arms

I think it was about our experience with the robotic arm and how much do we trust it to perform well. Since the robot performed really well in the easy task, I assumed it would do well in all other easy tasks and slightly worse in the medium/hard ones. I think the research is more related to our thoughts, trust and experiences as participants rather than just the ability of the arm.
